1
00:00:00,360 --> 00:00:03,600
Those who conducted the interrogations with us

2
00:00:03,759 --> 00:00:05,559
Were from inside the prison

3
00:00:05,679 --> 00:00:08,759
Like Abu Yousuf the interrogator and Abu Abdul Rahman

4
00:00:08,919 --> 00:00:10,800
The second one was from the al-Sahou clan

5
00:00:11,320 --> 00:00:15,640
The group deliberately used people in interrogations who had strong intelligence connections inside the city

6
00:00:16,879 --> 00:00:19,600
That’s one point, and the first and most important

7
00:00:20,120 --> 00:00:21,839
The most important and strongest thing they had

8
00:00:22,559 --> 00:00:24,839
Was that they had security agents inside the prison

9
00:00:25,239 --> 00:00:28,480
They had security agents from our own people, from our towns, sadly

10
00:00:28,559 --> 00:00:32,000
ISIS had security agents from our local people working inside the prison for money

11
00:00:32,479 --> 00:00:36,520
For example, someone would come, and I’d look at him, and one of them

12
00:00:37,079 --> 00:00:39,240
Was from the al-Bou Saraya clan, named Abdullah

13
00:00:39,479 --> 00:00:42,439
He sat beside me, and I had been in prison for 10 days

14
00:00:44,679 --> 00:00:50,719
When he sat and started crying, saying he was wronged and jailed over selling a pistol

15
00:00:50,799 --> 00:00:54,119
I trusted him, as I had nothing to hide

16
00:00:54,600 --> 00:00:57,920
The group’s informants or security men

17
00:00:58,159 --> 00:01:03,520
Would come acting like victims, saying they were innocent, and talk about ISIS in front of me, saying we’ll get out tomorrow

18
00:01:03,640 --> 00:01:06,959
And say, God is generous, and promise that such-and-such faction would enter the city

19
00:01:07,079 --> 00:01:10,239
So the person in front of them would confess and start talking

20
00:01:10,280 --> 00:01:15,519
These were the ones ISIS sent in as informants and internal agents

21
00:01:15,640 --> 00:01:17,439
They were very intelligent people

22
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:21,400
One of these people was named Abdullah al-Asaad

23
00:01:21,719 --> 00:01:25,640
His house was next to the Nabhan Glass Shop in Raqqa, and he was killed

24
00:01:27,120 --> 00:01:30,239
While fighting in one of the battles

25
00:01:30,599 --> 00:01:33,920
He started crying in front of me, and about 40 days later

26
00:01:34,319 --> 00:01:37,120
He started crying again and told me that his mother had died

27
00:01:38,159 --> 00:01:42,120
When I got out of prison, his goal was to get information from me

28
00:01:42,599 --> 00:01:46,200
When I was released, I went to his house to offer condolences to his father

29
00:01:46,239 --> 00:01:49,400
And I said, Keep your faith strong, Abdullah is crying and mourning his mother

30
00:01:49,439 --> 00:01:53,000
Since I had been released, it was my duty to visit my friend’s family who was still in prison

31
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:58,040
I was shocked when his mother came out, cursing him and saying, May God never grant him success, and that she had disowned him

32
00:01:58,280 --> 00:02:00,840
She said, He claims I’m dead, but he’s an informant for the group

33
00:02:02,040 --> 00:02:06,159
There were many people who infiltrated others in this same way

34
00:02:07,120 --> 00:02:09,240
Our people are kind-hearted and simple

35
00:02:09,719 --> 00:02:13,240
So they might slip and say something by mistake, and that security informant

36
00:02:13,800 --> 00:02:14,800
Would then

37
00:02:15,280 --> 00:02:20,319
Report it to the security forces, and based on that, the person would be accused. Many people were killed that way

38
00:02:21,400 --> 00:02:23,240
Stories like this were common
